    rationale: "AMINOGLYCOSIDE PHARMACOLOGY: Gentamicin, tobramycin, and amikacin are 30S ribosomal inhibitors with a UNIQUE mechanism: (1) UPTAKE: Aminoglycosides are polycationic molecules → bind to the negatively charged LPS of Gram-negative outer membranes → energy-dependent Phase I uptake (requires O₂-dependent electron transport — why aminoglycosides DON'T work against anaerobes). (2) RIBOSOMAL BINDING: Bind 16S rRNA of the 30S ribosomal subunit → cause MISREADING of mRNA codons → aberrant proteins are produced → misfolded proteins insert into the cell membrane → membrane damage → MORE aminoglycoside entry (self-enhancing uptake — 'lethal' misreading). (3) BACTERICIDAL: Unlike other ribosomal inhibitors (macrolides, tetracyclines — bacteriostatic), aminoglycosides are BACTERICIDAL because of this membrane disruption + irreversible 30S binding. CONCENTRATION-DEPENDENT KILLING: Higher peak → more initial ribosomal binding → more misread proteins → more membrane damage → faster kill. The RATE of killing is determined by Cmax/MIC, NOT time above MIC. POST-ANTIBIOTIC EFFECT (PAE): Even after drug concentration drops below MIC, bacteria remain suppressed 2-8 hours → drug-free interval is safe. EXTENDED-INTERVAL DOSING: (1) HIGH PEAK (20-30 μg/mL for gentamicin) → maximizes Cmax/MIC → superior killing. (2) DRUG-FREE TROUGH: Renal proximal tubule cells take up aminoglycosides via megalin receptor — uptake is SATURABLE. Continuous low-level exposure → continuous uptake → nephrotoxicity. Intermittent high peaks with troughs <1 μg/mL → saturated uptake during peak but NO uptake during trough → less total renal accumulation → less nephrotoxicity. Same principle: cochlear hair cell damage (ototoxicity) correlates with TOTAL drug exposure, not peak. SYNERGY WITH BETA-LACTAMS: Beta-lactam disrupts cell wall peptidoglycan → increased aminoglycoside intracellular penetration → up to 10-100× increased killing. Particularly important for Pseudomonas (double-coverage reduces resistance emergence) and Enterococcal endocarditis (synergistic bactericidal activity).",
