    rationale: "AMINOGLYCOSIDE THERAPEUTIC DRUG MONITORING (TDM): Extended-interval dosing targets: HIGH PEAK (Cmax optimization for concentration-dependent killing) + LOW TROUGH (minimize toxicity from sustained tissue accumulation). TARGET VALUES for tobramycin/gentamicin: Peak 20-30 μg/mL (drawn 30 min after infusion ends), Trough <1 μg/mL (drawn within 30 min before next dose). ELEVATED TROUGH INTERPRETATION: Trough 3.2 μg/mL means drug is NOT adequately cleared between doses. Causes: (1) Renal impairment (acute or chronic — aminoglycosides are >90% renally eliminated via glomerular filtration). (2) Dosing interval too short for patient's GFR. (3) Third-spacing (ascites, edema) with subsequent redistribution. TOXICITY IMPLICATIONS: (a) NEPHROTOXICITY: Proximal tubular cells take up aminoglycosides via megalin receptor on apical brush border → intracellular accumulation → lysosomal disruption → phospholipidosis → cell death → acute tubular necrosis. Uptake is CONTINUOUS when drug concentration exceeds a threshold → elevated trough = continuous uptake = more toxicity. Extended-interval dosing works because the drug-free period allows tubular cells to recover. (b) OTOTOXICITY: Aminoglycosides enter cochlear hair cells via mechanotransducer channels (normally for potassium entry during sound transduction) → mitochondrial damage → ROS generation → irreversible hair cell apoptosis. Vestibulotoxicity (gentamicin > tobramycin) vs cochleotoxicity (amikacin > tobramycin). ADJUSTMENT: EXTEND INTERVAL, MAINTAIN DOSE. Rationale: Dose determines PEAK (efficacy) → keep same dose to maintain adequate Cmax/MIC. Interval determines TROUGH (toxicity) → extend interval to allow trough to fall below 1 μg/mL. CF PATIENTS: Generally have INCREASED aminoglycoside clearance (higher GFR, larger Vd) → may need HIGHER doses and/or SHORTER intervals at baseline. However, years of aminoglycoside exposure can cause cumulative nephrotoxicity → declining clearance over time → needs ongoing TDM.",
