    rationale: "AZOLE ANTIFUNGAL MECHANISM: All azoles (fluconazole, itraconazole, voriconazole, posaconazole, isavuconazole) share the same primary target: LANOSTEROL 14-α-DEMETHYLASE (Erg11/CYP51A). This is a fungal cytochrome P450 enzyme in the ergosterol synthesis pathway: Acetyl-CoA → ... → Squalene → Lanosterol → [CYP51A] → 4,4-dimethylcholesta-8,14,24-trienol → ... → ERGOSTEROL. Azoles bind the HEME iron of CYP51A via the azole nitrogen → competitive inhibition → (1) NO ERGOSTEROL produced → membrane becomes rigid, leaky, non-functional. (2) TOXIC STEROL ACCUMULATION: 14-α-methylated lanosterol intermediates accumulate → insert into membrane → further disrupt bilayer fluidity and function. (3) DOWNSTREAM EFFECTS: membrane-bound enzymes malfunction → impaired nutrient uptake, chitin synthesis, oxidative phosphorylation. SELECTIVITY: Fungal CYP51A vs human CYP51 (lanosterol 14-α-demethylase involved in cholesterol synthesis) → azoles have ~100-1000× higher affinity for fungal enzyme → selective toxicity (though some cross-reactivity explains hepatotoxicity). VORICONAZOLE-TACROLIMUS INTERACTION: Voriconazole inhibits human CYP3A4 (plus CYP2C19, CYP2C9) → tacrolimus is primarily metabolized by CYP3A4 in liver and intestinal wall → CYP3A4 inhibition by voriconazole → DRAMATICALLY reduced tacrolimus clearance → 3-5× increase in tacrolimus AUC. CONSEQUENCES of supratherapeutic tacrolimus: (1) NEPHROTOXICITY: afferent arteriole vasoconstriction → reduced GFR → acute kidney injury (particularly devastating in transplant patients where kidney preservation is paramount). (2) NEUROTOXICITY: tremor, seizures, posterior reversible encephalopathy syndrome (PRES). (3) EXCESSIVE IMMUNOSUPPRESSION: paradoxically INCREASES infection risk. (4) Hyperkalemia, hyperglycemia, hypertension. MANAGEMENT: Reduce tacrolimus dose by ~66% when starting voriconazole. Check tacrolimus trough within 3-5 days. Voriconazole TDM also needed: target trough 1-5.5 μg/mL (subtherapeutic <1 → treatment failure; supratherapeutic >5.5 → hepatotoxicity, visual disturbances, QTc prolongation).",
    explanationA: "Voriconazole does NOT puncture membranes directly — that describes amphotericin B (which binds ergosterol and creates pores). Voriconazole INHIBITS ergosterol SYNTHESIS. The tacrolimus interaction is hepatic CYP3A4 inhibition, not renal tubular competition.",
    explanationB: "Voriconazole is an AZOLE, not an echinocandin. Echinocandins (caspofungin, micafungin, anidulafungin) inhibit β-1,3-glucan synthase. The voriconazole-tacrolimus interaction is pharmacokinetic (CYP3A4), not additive nephrotoxicity.",
    explanationC: "Azoles do NOT target fungal DNA synthesis. They target membrane sterol (ergosterol) synthesis. The tacrolimus interaction is primarily CYP3A4 inhibition in the liver (not intestinal P-gp, though voriconazole may have some P-gp effects, the dominant mechanism is CYP3A4).",
    explanationD: "Correct. CYP51A (lanosterol 14-α-demethylase) inhibition → ergosterol depletion + toxic sterol accumulation. CYP3A4 inhibition → tacrolimus accumulation (3-5×) → nephro/neurotoxicity. Reduce tacrolimus ~66% and monitor levels.",
    examTip: "Azole antifungal spectrum and CYP interactions: FLUCONAZOLE: Candida (not C. krusei — intrinsically resistant, reduced for C. glabrata), Cryptococcus. CYP2C9/2C19 inhibitor. VORICONAZOLE: Aspergillus (DOC for invasive aspergillosis), Candida, Fusarium, Scedosporium. CYP3A4/2C19/2C9 inhibitor. Nonlinear PK (requires TDM). POSACONAZOLE: Mucormycosis (prophylaxis and salvage), Aspergillus. CYP3A4 inhibitor. ISAVUCONAZOLE: Aspergillus, Mucormycosis (only azole with Mucor activity for treatment). Fewer CYP interactions than voriconazole. SHORTENS QTc (unique among azoles).",
